To dig each post hole, pull up the wooden peg and dig a hole approximately two feet deep, using a shovel and then a post hole digger. The post hole digger maintains the necessary width of the hole as it digs. When digging the post hole, a good rule of thumb is to make the hole deep enough to bury 1/3 of the length of the fence post. This gives them better stability, helping them to withstand heavy weight and high winds. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/84/Erect-a-Fence-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/8/84/Erect-a-Fence-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

The post hole should be 10 to 12 inches wide. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/66/Erect-a-Fence-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/66/Erect-a-Fence-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

When all of the fence posts have been erected, you will need to fill them using either concrete or post mix. If using concrete, fill each post hole with the wet cement (which you should prepare according to the instructions on the packaging) and use a stick to stir the wet mix while pouring to eliminate any air pockets. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/60/Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/6/60/Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Overfill the top of the hole with concrete, then use a trowel to slope the concrete away from the fence post. This prevents water from collecting around the base. Alternatively, you can stop pouring the concrete a couple of inches from the top of the whole, then fill with soil once the concrete is dry. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f8/Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/f/f8/Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you're using post mix (which has a significantly shorter drying time than concrete), you will need to half fill the post hole with water, then pour in the post mix until it reaches slightly below soil level. It is recommended that you wear a mask, goggles and gloves while you do this. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2d/Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/2d/Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-8Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

To attach the fence panels to the posts, you can either use rust resistant nails or exterior-grade brackets and screws. Using nails: Position each fence panel between two posts so that the edges of the panels reach the center of the posts. Use a spirit level across the top supporting rail to ensure the fence panel is level. Use 18d or 20d galvanized nails to attach the panel to the posts, through the top and bottom supporting rails. You may need another person to hold the panel in position as you do this. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/7b\/Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/7b\/Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet1.jpg\/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Using brackets and screws: Attach three brackets to the edges of each fence panel: one 8 inches from the top, one 8 inches from the bottom and one in the center. You can place a couple of off-cuts of gravel board, pressure-treated board, or spacer blocks at the base of each post to lift the fence panel off the ground while you work. Set each fence panel on top of the gravel boards then screw them to the posts. This prevents the wood from contacting the ground, where it would rot faster. (This three-rail system is the stronger option, but you can use two evenly spaced rails instead. ){"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/5e\/Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/5\/5e\/Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet2.jpg\/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}


Note: Some some store-bought fences will have mortise and tenon joints which you can simply slot into one another, instead of using nails or screws. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/ef\/Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet3.jpg\/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/e\/ef\/Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet3.jpg\/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-11Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Applying a protective finish to your fence will help to keep it looking good for longer. A paint finish will allow you to match your fence to the color of your home or other outdoor furniture. The wood should be completely dry before you paint it and coated in primer. Make sure to use an exterior latex paint. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4e/Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet1.jpg/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/4/4e/Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet1.jpg/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

Stains add a bit of life and color to the fence, while also preserving the natural look of the wood and allowing the grain to show through. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1a/Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet2.jpg/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/1/1a/Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet2.jpg/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A waterproof finish or repellent is necessary for woods that don't withstand moisture very well and are prone to decay. Such woods include spruce, poplar, birch and red oak. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/be/Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet3.jpg/v4-460px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/b/be/Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet3.jpg/v4-760px-Erect-a-Fence-Step-14Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":570,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}
